<H2><U>
<a name="figures">Important Kiowa Mythological Figures</a>
</u></H2>

<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U>Sendeh</font></U></B></I> (also spelled Sende, Senday, Sainday, Sayn-Day, and other ways.) 
Sendeh is the trickster/transformer culture hero of the Kiowa tribe. Unlike trickster spirits in most Plains Indian tribes, Sendeh is consistently depicted as a 
human man, not an animal such as a coyote or spider<B>;</B> and though traditional tales often revolve around Sendeh causing mischief, getting into
trouble, and behaving in humorously inappropriate ways, he is a generally benign character who does not commit villainous acts and often helps the Kiowa
people.



<H2><U>
<a name="tribes">Kiowa Indian Folklore</a>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/BearsLodge-Kiowa.html
">Story of the Bears' Lodge</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Kiowa legend about the origin of the Pleiades.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023034529/http://pyramidmesa.com/kiowa1.htm
">The Buffalo Go</a></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <B><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/ThePassingoftheBuffalo-Kiowa.html
">The Passing of the Buffalo</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
Kiowa stories about the destruction of the buffalo herds.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/LegendOfWolfBoy-Kiowa.html
">Legend of Wolf Boy</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Kiowa myth about a boy deceived by his wicked sister-in-law.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/SendehCheatsTheSoldier-Kiowa.html
">Sendeh Cheats The Soldier</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A funny Kiowa legend about the trickster fooling some soldiers.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/WhiteCrowHidesTheAnimals-Kiowa.html
">White Crow Hides the Animals</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Kiowa legend explaining why crows are scavengers.
<BR>

<H2><U>
<a name="books">Recommended Books on Kiowa Mythology</a>
</u><BR><font size=2>Our organization earns a commission from any book bought through these links</font>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0689852878/natilangofthe-20
">Hold Up The Sky</a>:</B> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Anthology of legends from the Kiowa and other Southern Plains tribes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1589792017/natilangofthe-20
">The First Fire</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Collection of stories from the Kickapoo, Cherokee, Kiowa, and Tigua tribes.
<BR>

